Time Limiter:

TimeLimiter works by waiting for a result with a timeout
This is simple, if any of the service is depending on other service Product depend on User service. then we will set the timelimit
  retry:
    instances:
      userServiceRetry:
        maxAttempts: 3
        waitDuration: 2s

BULKHEADS:
So if user service is not at all responding then product also get breaks , so bullkheads solves this 
if there are 20 threadpools are waiting for user to react then threadpools counts over then if user not responds it will break the product too.
So instead of sharing all the threads to user (20) we will islolate with dedicated threads
Types of Bulkhead

Resilience4j provides two types.

Type	                        Description
Semaphore Bulkhead	        Limits concurrent calls - mostly used
ThreadPool Bulkhead	        Separate thread pools


Semaphore Bulkhead:
resilience4j:
  bulkhead:
    instances:
      userServiceBulkhead:
        maxConcurrentCalls: 5
        maxWaitDuration: 0

Meaning:

Only 5 concurrent requests allowed to User Service

If a 6th request arrives:

Bulkhead rejects request
Fallback executed

| Layer          | Protects Against             |
| -------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Bulkhead       | too many concurrent requests |
| Retry          | temporary failures           |
| TimeLimiter    | slow responses               |
| CircuitBreaker | repeated failures            |
